# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conservation-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:conservation-biology/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had over two million copies printed and has been translated into at least fourteen languages.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] It has informed and changed the environmental movement and stimulated a widespread interest in ecology as a science.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] In the original publishing, the book begins with a set of essays under the heading "Sand County Almanac," which is divided into twelve segments, one for each month.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] These essays mostly follow the changes in the ecology on Leopold's farm near Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] (There is, in fact, no "Sand County" in Wisconsin.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The term "sand counties" refers to a section of the state marked by sandy soils).
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] There are anecdotes and observations about flora and fauna reactions to the seasons as well as mentions of conservation topics.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The second section of the book, "Sketches Here and There," shifts the rhetorical focus from time to place.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The essays are thematically organized around farms and wildernesses in Canada, Mexico and the United States.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] Some of these essays are autobiographical.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] "Red Legs Kicking," for example, recounts Leopold's boyhood experience of hunting in Iowa.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The seminal essay "Thinking Like a Mountain" recalls another hunting experience later in life that was formative for Leopold's later views.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold describes the death of a she-wolf killed by his party during a time when conservationists were operating under the assumption that elimination of top predators would make game plentiful.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The essay provides a non-technical characterization of the trophic cascade where the removal of single species carries serious implications for the rest of the ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The book ends with a section of philosophical essays grouped together under the heading "The Upshot".
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold explores ironies of conservation: in order to promote wider appreciation of wild nature and engender necessary political support, one encourages recreational usage of wilderness that ultimately destroys it.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] Musings on "trophies" contrasts the way that some need a physical specimen to prove their conquest into the wilderness, though photographs may be less damaging than a trophy head to be mounted on the wall.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] He suggests that the best trophy is the experience of wilderness itself, along with its character-building aspects.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold also rails against the way that policy makers need to find an economic motive for conservation.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] In the concluding essay, "The Land Ethic", Leopold delves into a more appropriate rationale for conservation.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] In "The Ecological Conscience" section, he wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." Leopold felt it was generally agreed that more conservation education was needed; however quantity and content were up for debate.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] He believed that land is not a commodity to be possessed; rather, humans must have mutual respect for Earth in order not to destroy it.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] He philosophizes that humans will cease to be free if they have no wild spaces in which to roam.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] In a 1990 poll of the membership by the American Nature Study Society, *A Sand County Almanac* and Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* stand alone as the two most venerated and significant environmental books of the 20th century.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The book was little noticed when published but, during the environmental awakening of the 1970s, a paperback edition turned into a surprise bestseller.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had immense popular influence and has been described as: "one of the benchmark titles of the ecological movement", "a major influence on American attitudes toward our natural environment", "recognized as a classic piece of outdoor literature, rivaling Thoreau's *Walden*".
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has also had great influence on environmental thinkers: "along with *Walden* and Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring*, one of the main intellectual underpinnings of environmentalism in America".
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has "attracted such overwhelming attention from environmental philosophers as a source of inspiration and ideas".
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold's home, Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm, was listed on the U.S.
[src:conservation-biology/a-sand-county-almanac] National Register of Historic Places in 1978, and was uplisted to National Historic Landmark status in 2009.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:conservation-biology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] The nouns *acclimatization* and *acclimation* (and the corresponding verbs *acclimatize* and *acclimate*) are widely regarded as synonymous, both in general vocabulary and in medical vocabulary.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] The synonym *acclimation* is less commonly encountered, and fewer dictionaries enter it.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] In order to maintain performance across a range of environmental conditions, there are several strategies organisms use to acclimate.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] In response to changes in temperature, organisms can change the biochemistry of cell membranes making them more fluid in cold temperatures and less fluid in warm temperatures by increasing the number of membrane proteins.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] In response to certain stressors, some organisms express so-called heat shock proteins that act as molecular chaperones and reduce denaturation by guiding the folding and refolding of proteins.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] It has been shown that organisms which are acclimated to high or low temperatures display relatively high resting levels of heat shock proteins so that when they are exposed to even more extreme temperatures the proteins are readily available.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Expression of heat shock proteins and regulation of membrane fluidity are just two of many biochemical methods organisms use to acclimate to novel environments.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Organisms are able to change several characteristics relating to their morphology in order to maintain performance in novel environments.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] For example, birds often increase their organ size to increase their metabolism.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] This can take the form of an increase in the mass of nutritional organs or heat-producing organs, like the pectorals (with the latter being more consistent across species).
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] While the capacity for acclimatization has been documented in thousands of species, researchers still know very little about how and why organisms acclimate in the way that they do.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Since researchers first began to study acclimation, the overwhelming hypothesis has been that all acclimation serves to enhance the performance of the organism.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] This idea has come to be known as the beneficial acclimation hypothesis.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Despite such widespread support for the beneficial acclimation hypothesis, not all studies show that acclimation always serves to enhance performance (*See beneficial acclimation hypothesis*).
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] One of the major objections to the beneficial acclimation hypothesis is that it assumes that there are no costs associated with acclimation.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] However, there are likely to be costs associated with acclimation.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] These include the cost of sensing the environmental conditions and regulating responses, producing structures required for plasticity (such as the energetic costs in expressing heat shock proteins), and genetic costs (such as linkage of plasticity-related genes with harmful genes).
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Given the shortcomings of the beneficial acclimation hypothesis, researchers are continuing to search for a theory that will be supported by empirical data.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] The degree to which organisms are able to acclimate is dictated by their phenotypic plasticity or the ability of an organism to change certain traits.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Recent research in the study of acclimation capacity has focused more heavily on the evolution of phenotypic plasticity rather than acclimation responses.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Scientists believe that when they understand more about how organisms evolved the capacity to acclimate, they will better understand acclimation.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Many plants, such as maple trees, irises, and tomatoes, can survive freezing temperatures if the temperature gradually drops lower and lower each night over a period of days or weeks.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] The same drop might kill them if it occurred suddenly.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Studies have shown that tomato plants that were acclimated to higher temperature over several days were more efficient at photosynthesis at relatively high temperatures than were plants that were not allowed to acclimate.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] In the orchid *Phalaenopsis*, phenylpropanoid enzymes are enhanced in the process of plant acclimatisation at different levels of photosynthetic photon flux.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Sheep grow very thick wool in cold, damp climates.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Fish are able to adjust only gradually to changes in water temperature and quality.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Tropical fish sold at pet stores are often kept in acclimatization bags until this process is complete.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Lowe & Vance (1995) were able to show that lizards acclimated to warm temperatures could maintain a higher running speed at warmer temperatures than lizards that were not acclimated to warm conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Fruit flies that develop at relatively cooler or warmer temperatures have increased cold or heat tolerance as adults, respectively (*See* Developmental plasticity).
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] The salt content of sweat and urine decreases as people acclimatize to hot conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Plasma volume, heart rate, and capillary activation are also affected.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Acclimatization to high altitude continues for months or even years after initial ascent, and ultimately enables humans to survive in an environment that, without acclimatization, would kill them.
[src:conservation-biology/acclimate] Humans who migrate permanently to a higher altitude naturally acclimatize to their new environment by developing an increase in the number of red blood cells to increase the oxygen carrying capacity of the blood, in order to compensate for lower levels of oxygen intake.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In biology, **adaptation** has three related meanings.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Firstly, it is the dynamic evolutionary process of natural selection that fits organisms to their environment, enhancing their evolutionary fitness.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Secondly, it is a state reached by the population during that process.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Thirdly, it is a phenotypic trait or **adaptive trait**, with a functional role in each individual organism, that is maintained and has evolved through natural selection.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Historically, adaptation has been described from the time of the ancient Greek philosophers such as Empedocles and Aristotle.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In 18th and 19th-century natural theology, adaptation was taken as evidence for the existence of a deity.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace proposed instead that it was explained by natural selection.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation is related to biological fitness, which governs the rate of evolution as measured by changes in allele frequencies.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Often, two or more species co-adapt and co-evolve as they develop adaptations that interlock with those of the other species, such as with flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In mimicry, species evolve to resemble other species; in mimicry this is a mutually beneficial co-evolution as each of a group of strongly defended species (such as wasps able to sting) come to advertise their defences in the same way.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Features evolved for one purpose may be co-opted for a different one, as when the insulating feathers of dinosaurs were co-opted for bird flight.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation is a major topic in the philosophy of biology, as it concerns function and purpose (teleology).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Some biologists try to avoid terms which imply purpose in adaptation, not least because they suggest a deity's intentions, but others note that adaptation is necessarily purposeful.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation is an observable fact of life accepted by philosophers and natural historians from ancient times, independently of their views on evolution, but their explanations differed.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Empedocles did not believe that adaptation required a final cause (a purpose), but thought that it "came about naturally, since such things survived." Aristotle did believe in final causes, but assumed that species were fixed.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In natural theology, adaptation was interpreted as the work of a deity and as evidence for the existence of God.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] William Paley believed that organisms were perfectly adapted to the lives they led, an argument that shadowed Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who had argued that God had brought about "the best of all possible worlds." Voltaire's satire Dr.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Pangloss is a parody of this optimistic idea, and David Hume also argued against design.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Charles Darwin broke with the tradition by emphasising the flaws and limitations which occurred in the animal and plant worlds.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck proposed a tendency for organisms to become more complex, moving up a ladder of progress, plus "the influence of circumstances", usually expressed as *use and disuse*.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This second, subsidiary element of his theory is what is now called Lamarckism, a proto-evolutionary hypothesis of the inheritance of acquired characteristics, intended to explain adaptations by natural means.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Other natural historians, such as Buffon, accepted adaptation, and some also accepted evolution, without voicing their opinions as to the mechanism.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This illustrates the real merit of Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, and secondary figures such as Henry Walter Bates, for putting forward a mechanism whose significance had only been glimpsed previously.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] A century later, experimental field studies and breeding experiments by people such as E.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Ford and Theodosius Dobzhansky produced evidence that natural selection was not only the 'engine' behind adaptation, but was a much stronger force than had previously been thought.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation is primarily a process rather than a physical form or part of a body.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] An internal parasite (such as a liver fluke) can illustrate the distinction: such a parasite may have a very simple bodily structure, but nevertheless the organism is highly adapted to its specific environment.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] From this we see that adaptation is not just a matter of visible traits: in such parasites critical adaptations take place in the life cycle, which is often quite complex.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] However, as a practical term, "adaptation" often refers to a *product*: those features of a species which result from the process.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Many aspects of an animal or plant can be correctly called adaptations, though there are always some features whose function remains in doubt.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary *process*, and *adaptive trait* for the bodily part or function (the product), one may distinguish the two different senses of the word.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation is one of the two main processes that explain the observed diversity of species, such as the different species of Darwin's finches.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The other process is speciation, in which new species arise, typically through reproductive isolation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] An example widely used today to study the interplay of adaptation and speciation is the evolution of cichlid fish in African lakes, where the question of reproductive isolation is complex.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation is not always a simple matter where the ideal phenotype evolves for a given environment.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] An organism must be viable at all stages of its development and at all stages of its evolution.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This places *constraints* on the evolution of development, behaviour, and structure of organisms.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The main constraint, over which there has been much debate, is the requirement that each genetic and phenotypic change during evolution should be relatively small, because developmental systems are so complex and interlinked.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] However, it is not clear what "relatively small" should mean, for example polyploidy in plants is a reasonably common large genetic change.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The origin of eukaryotic endosymbiosis is a more dramatic example.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] All adaptations help organisms survive in their ecological niches.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The adaptive traits may be structural, behavioural or physiological.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Structural adaptations are physical features of an organism, such as shape, body covering, armament, and internal organization.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Behavioural adaptations are inherited systems of behaviour, whether inherited in detail as instincts, or as a neuropsychological capacity for learning.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Examples include searching for food, mating, and vocalizations.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Physiological adaptations permit the organism to perform special functions such as making venom, secreting slime, and phototropism, but also involve more general functions such as growth and development, temperature regulation, ionic balance and other aspects of homeostasis.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation affects all aspects of the life of an organism.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation differs from flexibility, acclimatization, and learning, all of which are changes during life which are not inherited.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Flexibility deals with the relative capacity of an organism to maintain itself in different habitats: its degree of specialization.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Acclimatization describes automatic physiological adjustments during life; learning means alteration in behavioural performance during life.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Flexibility stems from phenotypic plasticity, the ability of an organism with a given genotype (genetic type) to change its phenotype (observable characteristics) in response to changes in its habitat, or to move to a different habitat.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The degree of flexibility is inherited, and varies between individuals.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] A highly specialized animal or plant lives only in a well-defined habitat, eats a specific type of food, and cannot survive if its needs are not met.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Many herbivores are like this; extreme examples are koalas which depend on *Eucalyptus*, and giant pandas which require bamboo.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] A generalist, on the other hand, eats a range of food, and can survive in many different conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Examples are humans, rats, crabs and many carnivores.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The *tendency* to behave in a specialized or exploratory manner is inherited—it is an adaptation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Rather different is developmental flexibility: "An animal or plant is developmentally flexible if when it is raised in or transferred to new conditions, it changes in structure so that it is better fitted to survive in the new environment," writes the evolutionary biologist John Maynard Smith.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] If humans move to a higher altitude, respiration and physical exertion become a problem, but after spending time in high altitude conditions they acclimatize to the reduced partial pressure of oxygen, such as by producing more red blood cells.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The ability to acclimatize is an adaptation, but the acclimatization itself is not.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The reproductive rate declines, but deaths from some tropical diseases also go down.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Over a longer period of time, some people are better able to reproduce at high altitudes than others.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] They contribute more heavily to later generations, and gradually by natural selection the whole population becomes adapted to the new conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This has demonstrably occurred, as the observed performance of long-term communities at higher altitude is significantly better than the performance of new arrivals, even when the new arrivals have had time to acclimatize.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] There is a relationship between adaptedness and the concept of fitness used in population genetics.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Differences in fitness between genotypes predict the rate of evolution by natural selection.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Natural selection changes the relative frequencies of alternative phenotypes, insofar as they are heritable.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] However, a phenotype with high adaptedness may not have high fitness.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Dobzhansky mentioned the example of the Californian redwood, which is highly adapted, but a relict species in danger of extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Elliott Sober commented that adaptation was a retrospective concept since it implied something about the history of a trait, whereas fitness predicts a trait's future.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The absolute contribution to the next generation by a genotype or a class of genotypes.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] when applied to the population as a whole.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The extent to which a phenotype fits its local ecological niche.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Sewall Wright proposed that populations occupy *adaptive peaks* on a fitness landscape.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] To evolve to another, higher peak, a population would first have to pass through a valley of maladaptive intermediate stages, and might be "trapped" on a peak that is not optimally adapted.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Before Darwin, adaptation was seen as a fixed relationship between an organism and its habitat.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] It was not appreciated that as the climate changed, so did the habitat; and as the habitat changed, so did the biota.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Also, habitats are subject to changes in their biota: for example, invasions of species from other areas.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The relative numbers of species in a given habitat are always changing.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Change is the rule, though much depends on the speed and degree of the change.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] When the habitat changes, three main things may happen to a resident population: habitat tracking, genetic change or extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In fact, all three things may occur in sequence.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Of these three effects only genetic change brings about adaptation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] When a habitat changes, the resident population typically moves to more suitable places; this is the typical response of flying insects or oceanic organisms, which have wide (though not unlimited) opportunity for movement.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This common response is called *habitat tracking*.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] It is one explanation put forward for the periods of apparent stasis in the fossil record (the punctuated equilibrium theory).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Without mutation, the ultimate source of all genetic variation, there would be no genetic changes and no subsequent adaptation through evolution by natural selection.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Genetic change occurs in a population when mutation increases or decreases in its initial frequency followed by random genetic drift, migration, recombination or natural selection act on this genetic variation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] One example is that the first pathways of enzyme-based metabolism at the very origin of life on Earth may have been co-opted components of the already-existing purine nucleotide metabolism, a metabolic pathway that evolved in an ancient RNA world.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The co-option requires new mutations and through natural selection, the population then adapts genetically to its present circumstances.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Genetic changes may result in entirely new or gradual change to visible structures, or they may adjust physiological activity in a way that suits the habitat.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The varying shapes of the beaks of Darwin's finches, for example, are driven by adaptive mutations in the ALX1 gene.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The coat color of different wild mouse species matches their environments, whether black lava or light sand, owing to adaptive mutations in the melanocortin 1 receptor and other melanin pathway genes.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Physiological resistance to the heart poisons (cardiac glycosides) that monarch butterflies store in their bodies to protect themselves from predators are driven by adaptive mutations in the target of the poison, the sodium pump, resulting in target site insensitivity.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] These same adaptive mutations and similar changes at the same amino acid sites were found to evolve in a parallel manner in distantly related insects that feed on the same plants, and even in a bird that feeds on monarchs through convergent evolution, a hallmark of adaptation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Convergence at the gene-level across distantly related species can arise because of evolutionary constraint.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Habitats and biota do frequently change over time and space.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Therefore, it follows that the process of adaptation is never fully complete.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Over time, it may happen that the environment changes little, and the species comes to fit its surroundings better and better, resulting in stabilizing selection.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] On the other hand, it may happen that changes in the environment occur suddenly, and then the species becomes less and less well adapted.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The only way for it to climb back up that fitness peak is via the introduction of new genetic variation for natural selection to act upon.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Seen like this, adaptation is a genetic *tracking process*, which goes on all the time to some extent, but especially when the population cannot or does not move to another, less hostile area.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Given enough genetic change, as well as specific demographic conditions, an adaptation may be enough to bring a population back from the brink of extinction in a process called evolutionary rescue.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptation does affect, to some extent, every species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Leigh Van Valen thought that even in a stable environment, because of antagonistic species interactions and limited resources, a species must constantly had to adapt to maintain its relative standing.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This became known as the Red Queen hypothesis, as seen in host-parasite interactions.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Existing genetic variation and mutation were the traditional sources of material on which natural selection could act.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In addition, horizontal gene transfer is possible between organisms in different species, using mechanisms as varied as gene cassettes, plasmids, transposons and viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In coevolution, where the existence of one species is tightly bound up with the life of another species, new or 'improved' adaptations which occur in one species are often followed by the appearance and spread of corresponding features in the other species.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In other words, each species triggers reciprocal natural selection in the other.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] These co-adaptational relationships are intrinsically dynamic, and may continue on a trajectory for millions of years, as has occurred in the relationship between flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Bates' work on Amazonian butterflies led him to develop the first scientific account of mimicry, especially the kind of mimicry which bears his name: Batesian mimicry.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] This is the mimicry by a palatable species of an unpalatable or noxious species (the model), gaining a selective advantage as predators avoid the model and therefore also the mimic.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Mimicry is thus an anti-predator adaptation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] A common example seen in temperate gardens is the hoverfly (Syrphidae), many of which—though bearing no sting—mimic the warning coloration of aculeate Hymenoptera (wasps and bees).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Such mimicry does not need to be perfect to improve the survival of the palatable species.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Bates, Wallace and Fritz Müller believed that Batesian and Müllerian mimicry provided evidence for the action of natural selection, a view which is now standard amongst biologists.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] All adaptations have a downside: horse legs are great for running on grass, but they cannot scratch their backs; mammals' hair helps temperature, but offers a niche for ectoparasites; the only flying penguins do is under water.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Adaptations serving different functions may be mutually destructive.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Compromise and makeshift occur widely, not perfection.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Selection pressures pull in different directions, and the adaptation that results is some kind of compromise.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Consider the antlers of the Irish elk, (often supposed to be far too large; in deer antler size has an allometric relationship to body size).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Antlers serve positively for defence against predators, and to score victories in the annual rut.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] But they are costly in terms of resources.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Their size during the last glacial period presumably depended on the relative gain and loss of reproductive capacity in the population of elks during that time.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] As another example, camouflage to avoid detection is destroyed when vivid coloration is displayed at mating time.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Here the risk to life is counterbalanced by the necessity for reproduction.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Stream-dwelling salamanders, such as Caucasian salamander or Gold-striped salamander have very slender, long bodies, perfectly adapted to life at the banks of fast small rivers and mountain brooks.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Elongated body protects their larvae from being washed out by current.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] However, elongated body increases risk of desiccation and decreases dispersal ability of the salamanders; it also negatively affects their fecundity.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] As a result, fire salamander, less perfectly adapted to the mountain brook habitats, is in general more successful, have a higher fecundity and broader geographic range.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The peacock's ornamental train (grown anew in time for each mating season) is a famous adaptation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] It must reduce his maneuverability and flight, and is hugely conspicuous; also, its growth costs food resources.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The recognition of sexual selection was for a long time in abeyance, but has been rehabilitated.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The conflict between the size of the human foetal brain at birth, (which cannot be larger than about 400 cm3, else it will not get through the mother's pelvis) and the size needed for an adult brain (about 1400 cm3), means the brain of a newborn child is quite immature.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The most vital things in human life (locomotion, speech) just have to wait while the brain grows and matures.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] That is the result of the birth compromise.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Much of the problem comes from our upright bipedal stance, without which our pelvis could be shaped more suitably for birth.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] As another example, the long neck of a giraffe brings benefits but at a cost.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The neck of a giraffe can be up to 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in length.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The benefits are that it can be used for inter-species competition or for foraging on tall trees where shorter herbivores cannot reach.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The cost is that a long neck is heavy and adds to the animal's body mass, requiring additional energy to build the neck and to carry its weight around.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Pre-adaptation occurs when a population has characteristics which by chance are suited for a set of conditions not previously experienced.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] For example, the polyploid cordgrass *Spartina townsendii* is better adapted than either of its parent species to their own habitat of saline marsh and mud-flats.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Among domestic animals, the White Leghorn chicken is markedly more resistant to vitamin B1 deficiency than other breeds; on a plentiful diet this makes no difference, but on a restricted diet this preadaptation could be decisive.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Pre-adaptation may arise because a natural population carries a huge quantity of genetic variability.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In diploid eukaryotes, this is a consequence of the system of sexual reproduction, where mutant alleles get partially shielded, for example, by genetic dominance.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Microorganisms, with their huge populations, also carry a great deal of genetic variability.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The word is controversial because it is teleological and the entire concept of natural selection depends on the presence of genetic variation, regardless of the population size of a species in question.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Features that now appear as adaptations sometimes arose by co-option of existing traits, evolved for some other purpose.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The classic example is the ear ossicles of mammals, which we know from paleontological and embryological evidence originated in the upper and lower jaws and the hyoid bone of their synapsid ancestors, and further back still were part of the gill arches of early fish.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The word *exaptation* was coined to cover these common evolutionary shifts in function.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The flight feathers of birds evolved from the much earlier feathers of dinosaurs, which might have been used for insulation or for display.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Animals including earthworms, beavers and humans use some of their adaptations to modify their surroundings, so as to maximize their chances of surviving and reproducing.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Beavers create dams and lodges, changing the ecosystems of the valleys around them.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Earthworms, as Darwin noted, improve the topsoil in which they live by incorporating organic matter.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Humans have constructed extensive civilizations with cities in environments as varied as the Arctic and hot deserts.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In all three cases, the construction and maintenance of ecological niches helps drive the continued selection of the genes of these animals, in an environment that the animals have modified.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Some traits do not appear to be adaptive as they have a neutral or deleterious effect on fitness in the current environment.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Another possibility is that a trait may have been adaptive at some point in an organism's evolutionary history, but a change in habitats caused what used to be an adaptation to become unnecessary or even maladapted.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Many organisms have vestigial organs, which are the remnants of fully functional structures in their ancestors.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] As a result of changes in lifestyle the organs became redundant, and are either not functional or reduced in functionality.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Since any structure represents some kind of cost to the general economy of the body, an advantage may accrue from their elimination once they are not functional.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Examples: wisdom teeth in humans; the loss of pigment and functional eyes in cave fauna; the loss of structure in endoparasites.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] If a population cannot move or change sufficiently to preserve its long-term viability, then it will become extinct, at least in that locale.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The species may or may not survive in other locales.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Species extinction occurs when the death rate over the entire species exceeds the birth rate for a long enough period for the species to disappear.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] It was an observation of Van Valen that groups of species tend to have a characteristic and fairly regular rate of extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The first stage in the evolution of life on earth is often hypothesized to be the RNA world in which short self-replicating RNA molecules proliferated before the evolution of DNA and proteins.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] By this hypothesis, life started when RNA chains began to self-replicate, initiating the three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation of type, and competition for resources.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The fitness of an RNA replicator (its per capita rate of increase) would likely have been a function of its intrinsic adaptive capacities, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and the availability of resources.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The three primary adaptive capacities may have been: (1) replication with moderate fidelity, giving rise to heritability while allowing variation of type, (2) resistance to decay, and (3) acquisition of resources.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] These adaptive capacities would have been determined by the folded configurations of the RNA replicators resulting from their nucleotide sequences.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] In his biology, Aristotle introduced teleology to describe the adaptedness of organisms, but without accepting the supernatural intention built into Plato's thinking, which Aristotle rejected.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] Modern biologists continue to face the same difficulty.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] On the one hand, adaptation is purposeful: natural selection chooses what works and eliminates what does not.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] On the other hand, biologists by and large reject conscious purpose in evolution.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptation] The dilemma gave rise to a famous joke by the evolutionary biologist Haldane: "Teleology is like a mistress to a biologist: he cannot live without her but he's unwilling to be seen with her in public.'" David Hull commented that Haldane's mistress "has become a lawfully wedded wife.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The achievement of these objectives requires an open management process which seeks to include past, present and future stakeholders.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management needs to at least maintain political openness, but usually aims to create it.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management must therefore be a scientific and social process.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] It must focus on the development of new institutions and institutional strategies in balance with scientific hypothesis and experimental frameworks (resilience.org).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management can proceed as either passive or active adaptive management, depending on how learning takes place.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Passive adaptive management values learning only insofar as it improves decision outcomes (i.e. passively), as measured by the specified utility function.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In contrast, active adaptive management explicitly incorporates learning as part of the objective function, and hence, decisions which improve learning are valued over those which do not.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In both cases, as new knowledge is gained, the models are updated and optimal management strategies are derived accordingly.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Thus, while learning occurs in both cases, it is treated differently.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Often, deriving actively adaptive policies is technically very difficult, which prevents it being more commonly applied.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The use of adaptive management techniques can be traced back to peoples from ancient civilisations.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] For example, the Yap people of Micronesia have been using adaptive management techniques to sustain high population densities in the face of resource scarcity for thousands of years (Falanruw 1984).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In using these techniques, the Yap people have altered their environment creating, for example, coastal mangrove depressions and seagrass meadows to support fishing and termite resistant wood (Stankey and Shinder 1997).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The origin of the adaptive management concept can be traced back to ideas of scientific management pioneered by Frederick Taylor in the early 1900s (Haber 1964).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] While the term "adaptive management" evolved in natural resource management workshops through decision makers, managers and scientists focussing on building simulation models to uncover key assumptions and uncertainties.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Two ecologists at The University of British Columbia, C.S.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Holling and C.J Walters further developed the adaptive management approach as they distinguished between passive and active adaptive management practice.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Kai Lee, notable Princeton physicist, expanded upon the approach in the late 1970s and early 1980s while pursuing a post-doctorate degree at UC Berkeley.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The approach was further developed at the International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis (IIASA) in Vienna, Austria, while C.S.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In 1992, Hilbourne described three learning models for federal land managers, around which adaptive management approaches could be developed, these are reactive, passive and active.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management has probably been most frequently applied in Yap, Australia and North America, initially applied in fishery management, but received more broad application in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] One of the most successful applications of adaptive management has been in the area of waterfowl harvest management in North America, most notably for the mallard.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management in a conservation project and program context can trace its roots back to at least the early 1990s, with the establishment of the Biodiversity Support Program (BSP) in 1989.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] BSP was a USAID-funded consortium of WWF, The Nature Conservancy (TNC), and World Resources Institute (WRI).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Its Analysis and Adaptive Management Program sought to understand the conditions under which certain conservation strategies were most effective and to identify lessons learned across conservation projects.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] When BSP ended in 2001, TNC and Foundations of Success (FOS, a non-profit which grew out of BSP) continued to actively work in promoting adaptive management for conservation projects and programs.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The approaches used included Conservation by Design (TNC) and Measures of Success (FOS).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In 2004, the Conservation Measures Partnership (CMP) – which includes several former BSP members – developed a common set of standards and guidelines for applying adaptive management to conservation projects and programs.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Applying adaptive management in a conservation or ecosystem management project involves the integration of project/program design, management, and monitoring to systematically test assumptions in order to adapt and learn.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The concept of adaptive management is not restricted to natural resources or ecosystem management, as similar concepts have been applied to international development programming.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This has often been a recognition to the "wicked" nature of many development challenges and the limits of traditional planning processes.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] One of the principal changes facing international development organizations is the need to be more flexible, adaptable and focused on learning.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This is reflected in international development approaches such as Doing Development Differently, Politically Informed Programming and Problem Driven Iterative Adaptation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] One recent example of the use of adaptive management by international development donors is the planned Global Learning for Adaptive Management (GLAM) programme to support adaptive management in Department for International Development and USAID.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The program is establishing a centre for learning about adaptive management to support the utilization and accessibility of adaptive management.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In addition, donors have been focused on amending their own programmatic guidance to reflect the importance of learning within programs: for instance, USAID's recent focus in their ADS guidance on the importance of collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This is also reflected in Department for International Development's Smart Rules that provide the operating framework for their programs including the use of evidence to inform their decisions.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] There are a variety of tools used to operationalize adaptive management in programs, such as learning agendas and decision cycles.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Collaborating, learning and adapting (CLA) is a concept related to the operationalizing of adaptive management in international development that describes a specific way of designing, implementing, adapting and evaluating programs.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] 3. adapting strategically based on applied learning.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] CLA practices have tangible benefits; for instance, a recent study recently found that companies "which apply more data-driven and adaptive leadership practices perform better" when examined against those which focus less on those practices.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] CLA integrates three closely connected concepts within the organizational theory literature: namely collaborating, learning and adapting.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] There is evidence of the benefits of collaborating internally within an organization and externally with organizations.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Much of the production and transmission of knowledge—both explicit knowledge and tacit knowledge—occurs through collaboration.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] There is evidence for the importance of collaboration among individuals and groups for innovation, knowledge production, and diffusion—for example, the benefits of staff interacting with one another and transmitting knowledge.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The importance of collaboration is closely linked to the ability of organizations to collectively learn from each other, a concept noted in the literature on learning organizations.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] CLA has been linked to a part of USAID's commitment to becoming a learning organization.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] CLA represents an approach to combine strategic collaboration, continuous learning, and adaptive management.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] A part of integrating the CLA approach is providing tools and resources, such as the Learning Lab, to staff and partner organizations.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The CLA approach is detailed for USAID staff in the recently revised program policy guidance.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a systematic process for improving environmental management policies and practices is the traditional application however, the adaptive management framework can also be applied to other sectors seeking sustainability solutions such as business and community development.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management as a strategy emphasizes the need to change with the environment and to learn from doing.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Adaptive management applied to ecosystems makes overt sense when considering ever changing environmental conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The flexibility and constant learning of an adaptive management approach is also a logical application for organizations seeking sustainability methodologies.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Businesses pursuing sustainability strategies would employ an adaptive management framework to ensure that the organization is prepared for the unexpected and geared for change.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] By applying an adaptive management approach the business begins to function as an integrated system adjusting and learning from a multi-faceted network of influences not just environmental but also, economic and social (Dunphy, Griffths, & Benn, 2007).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The goal of any sustainable organization guided by adaptive management principals must be to engage in active learning to direct change towards sustainability (Verine, 2008).
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This "learning to manage by managing to learn" (Bormann BT, 1993) will be at the core of a sustainable business strategy.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Sustainable community development requires recognition of the relationship between environment, economics and social instruments within the community.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] An adaptive management approach to creating sustainable community policy and practice also emphasizes the connection and confluence of those elements.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] A practical example of adaptive management as a tool for sustainability was the application of a modified variation of adaptive management using artvoice, photovoice, and agent-based modeling in a participatory social framework of action.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This application was used in field research on tribal lands to first identify the environmental issue and impact of illegal trash dumping and then to discover a solution through iterative agent-based modeling using NetLogo on a theoretical "regional cooperative clean-energy economy".
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This cooperative economy incorporated a mixed application of: traditional trash recycling and a waste-to-fuels process of carbon recycling of non-recyclable trash into ethanol fuel.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This industrial waste-to-fuels application was inspired by pioneering work of the Canadian-based company, Enerkem.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] See Bruss, 2012 - PhD dissertation: Human Environment Interactions and Collaborative Adaptive Capacity Building in a Resilience Framework, GDPE Colorado State University.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] It is difficult to test the effectiveness of adaptive management in comparison to other management approaches.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] One challenge is that once a system is managed using one approach it is difficult to determine how another approach would have performed in exactly the same situation.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] One study tested the effectiveness of formal passive adaptive management in comparison to human intuition by having natural resource management students make decisions about how to harvest a hypothetical fish population in an online computer game.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The students on average performed poorly in comparison to the computer programs implementing passive adaptive management.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Collaborative adaptive management is often celebrated as an effective way to deal with natural resource management under high levels of conflict, uncertainty and complexity.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The effectiveness of these efforts can be constrained by both social and technical barriers.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] In Colorado, USA, a ten-year, ranch-scale (2590 ha) experiment began in 2012 at the Agricultural Research Service (ARS) Central Plains Experimental range to evaluate the effectiveness and process of collaborative adaptive management on rangelands.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] The Collaborative Adaptive Rangeland Management or “CARM” project monitors outcomes from yearling steer grazing management on 10, 130 ha pastures conducted by a group of conservationists, ranchers, and public employees, and researchers.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] This team compares ecological monitoring data tracking profitability and conservation outcomes with outcomes from a “traditional” management treatment: a second set of ten pastures managed without adaptive decision making but with the same stocking rate.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Early evaluations of the project by social scientists offer insights for more effective adaptive management.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] First, trust is primary and essential to learning in adaptive management, not a side benefit.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Second, practitioners cannot assume that extensive monitoring data or large-scale efforts will automatically facilitate successful collaborative adaptive management.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Active, long-term efforts to build trust among scientists and stakeholders are also important.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Finally, explicit efforts to understand, share and respect multiple types of manager knowledge, including place-based ecological knowledge practiced by local managers, is necessary to manage adaptively for multiple conservation and livelihood goals on rangelands.
[src:conservation-biology/adaptive-management] Practitioners can expect adaptive management to be a complex, non-linear process shaped by social, political and ecological processes, as well as by data collection and interpretation.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:conservation-biology/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The conservation ethic is based on the findings of conservation biology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The term conservation biology and its conception as a new field originated with the convening of "The First International Conference on Research in Conservation Biology" held at the University of California, San Diego in La Jolla, California, in 1978 led by American biologists Bruce A.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Soulé with a group of leading university and zoo researchers and conservationists including Kurt Benirschke, Sir Otto Frankel, Thomas Lovejoy, and Jared Diamond.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The meeting was prompted due to concern over tropical deforestation, disappearing species, and eroding genetic diversity within species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The conference and proceedings that resulted sought to initiate the bridging of a gap between theory in ecology and evolutionary genetics on the one hand and conservation policy and practice on the other.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology and the concept of biological diversity (biodiversity) emerged together, helping crystallize the modern era of conservation science and policy.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The inherent multidisciplinary basis for conservation biology has led to new subdisciplines including conservation social science, conservation behavior and conservation physiology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] It stimulated further development of conservation genetics which Otto Frankel had originated first but is now often considered a subdiscipline as well.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The rapid decline of established biological systems around the world means that conservation biology is often referred to as a "Discipline with a deadline".
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology is tied closely to ecology in researching the population ecology (dispersal, migration, demographics, effective population size, inbreeding depression, and minimum population viability) of rare or endangered species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology is concerned with phenomena that affect the maintenance, loss, and restoration of biodiversity and the science of sustaining evolutionary processes that engender genetic, population, species, and ecosystem diversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The concern stems from estimates suggesting that up to 50% of all species on the planet will disappear within the next 50 years, which will increase poverty and starvation, and will reset the course of evolution on this planet.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Researchers acknowledge that projections are difficult, given the unknown potential impacts of many variables, including species introduction to new biogeographical settings and a non-analog climate.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists research and educate on the trends and process of biodiversity loss, species extinctions, and the negative effect these are having on our capabilities to sustain the well-being of human society.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists work in the field and office, in government, universities, non-profit organizations and industry.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The topics of their research are diverse, because this is an interdisciplinary network with professional alliances in the biological as well as social sciences.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Those dedicated to the cause and profession advocate for a global response to the current biodiversity crisis based on morals, ethics, and scientific reason.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Organizations and citizens are responding to the biodiversity crisis through conservation action plans that direct research, monitoring, and education programs that engage concerns at local through global scales.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There is increasing recognition that conservation is not just about what is achieved but how it is done.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conscious efforts to conserve and protect *global* biodiversity are a recent phenomenon.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Natural resource conservation, however, has a history that extends prior to the age of conservation.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Resource ethics grew out of necessity through direct relations with nature.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Regulation or communal restraint became necessary to prevent selfish motives from taking more than could be locally sustained, therefore compromising the long-term supply for the rest of the community.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This social dilemma with respect to natural resource management is often called the "tragedy of the commons".
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] From this principle, conservation biologists can trace communal resource based ethics throughout cultures as a solution to communal resource conflict.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] For example, the Alaskan Tlingit peoples and the Haida of the Pacific Northwest had resource boundaries, rules, and restrictions among clans with respect to the fishing of sockeye salmon.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] These rules were guided by clan elders who knew lifelong details of each river and stream they managed.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There are numerous examples in history where cultures have followed rules, rituals, and organized practice with respect to communal natural resource management.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The Mauryan emperor Ashoka around 250 BC issued edicts restricting the slaughter of animals and certain kinds of birds, as well as opened veterinary clinics.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation ethics are also found in early religious and philosophical writings.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There are examples in the Tao, Shinto, Hindu, Islamic and Buddhist traditions.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Before the 18th century, however, much of European culture considered it a pagan view to admire nature.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Wilderness was denigrated while agricultural development was praised.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] However, as early as AD 680 a wildlife sanctuary was founded on the Farne Islands by St Cuthbert in response to his religious beliefs.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Natural history was a major preoccupation in the 18th century, with grand expeditions and the opening of popular public displays in Europe and North America.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] By 1900 there were 150 natural history museums in Germany, 250 in Great Britain, 250 in the United States, and 300 in France.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Preservationist or conservationist sentiments are a development of the late 18th to early 20th centuries.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Before Charles Darwin set sail on HMS *Beagle*, most people in the world, including Darwin, believed in special creation and that all species were unchanged.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon was one of the first naturalists that questioned this belief.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] He proposed in his 44 volume natural history book that species evolve due to environmental influences.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Erasmus Darwin was also a naturalist who also suggested that species evolved.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Erasmus Darwin noted that some species have vestigial structures which are anatomical structures that have no apparent function in the species currently but would have been useful for the species' ancestors.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The thinking of these early 18th century naturalists helped to change the mindset and thinking of the early 19th century naturalists.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] By the early 19th century biogeography was ignited through the efforts of Alexander von Humboldt, Charles Lyell and Charles Darwin.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The 19th-century fascination with natural history engendered a fervor to be the first to collect rare specimens with the goal of doing so before they became extinct by other such collectors.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Although the work of many 18th and 19th century naturalists were to inspire nature enthusiasts and conservation organizations, their writings, by modern standards, showed insensitivity towards conservation as they would kill hundreds of specimens for their collections.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The modern roots of conservation biology can be found in the late 18th-century Enlightenment period particularly in England and Scotland.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Thinkers including Lord Monboddo described the importance of "preserving nature"; much of this early emphasis had its origins in Christian theology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Scientific conservation principles were first practically applied to the forests of British India.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The Madras Board of Revenue started local conservation efforts in 1842, headed by Alexander Gibson, a professional botanist who systematically adopted a forest conservation program based on scientific principles.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This was the first case of state conservation management of forests in the world.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Governor-General Lord Dalhousie introduced the first permanent and large-scale forest conservation program in the world in 1855, a model that soon spread to other colonies, as well the United States, where Yellowstone National Park was opened in 1872 as the world's first national park.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The term *conservation* came into widespread use in the late 19th century and referred to the management, mainly for economic reasons, of such natural resources as timber, fish, game, topsoil, pastureland, and minerals.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In addition it referred to the preservation of forests (forestry), wildlife (wildlife refuge), parkland, wilderness, and watersheds.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This period also saw the passage of the first conservation legislation and the establishment of the first nature conservation societies.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The Sea Birds Preservation Act 1869 was passed in Britain as the first nature protection law in the world after extensive lobbying from the Association for the Protection of Seabirds and the respected ornithologist Alfred Newton.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Newton was also instrumental in the passage of the first Game laws from 1872, which protected animals during their breeding season so as to prevent the stock from being brought close to extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] One of the first conservation societies was the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, founded in 1889 in Manchester as a protest group campaigning against the use of great crested grebe and kittiwake skins and feathers in fur clothing.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Originally known as "the Plumage League", the group gained popularity and eventually amalgamated with the Fur and Feather League in Croydon, and formed the RSPB.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This meeting led to the formation of the Society for the Promotion of Nature Reserves, which later became the Wildlife Trusts.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In the United States, the Forest Reserve Act of 1891 gave the President power to set aside forest reserves from the land in the public domain.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] John Muir founded the Sierra Club in 1892, and the New York Zoological Society was set up in 1895.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] A series of national forests and preserves were established by Theodore Roosevelt from 1901 to 1909.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The 1916 National Parks Act, included a 'use without impairment' clause, sought by John Muir, which eventually resulted in the removal of a proposal to build a dam in Dinosaur National Monument in 1959.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In the 20th century, Canadian civil servants, including Charles Gordon Hewitt and James Harkin, spearheaded the movement toward wildlife conservation.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In the 21st century professional conservation officers have begun to collaborate with indigenous communities for protecting wildlife in Canada.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Some conservation efforts are yet to fully take hold due to ecological neglect.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] For example in the USA, 21st century bowfishing of native fishes, which amounts to killing wild animals for recreation and disposing of them immediately afterwards, remains unregulated and unmanaged.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In the mid-20th century, efforts arose to target individual species for conservation, notably efforts in big cat conservation in South America led by the New York Zoological Society.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Akeley, Archie Carr and his son Archie Carr III is notable in this era.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Akeley for example, having led expeditions to the Virunga Mountains and observed the mountain gorilla in the wild, became convinced that the species and the area were conservation priorities.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] He was instrumental in persuading Albert I of Belgium to act in defense of the mountain gorilla and establish Albert National Park (since renamed Virunga National Park) in what is now Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] By the 1970s, led primarily by work in the United States under the Endangered Species Act along with the Species at Risk Act (SARA) of Canada, Biodiversity Action Plans developed in Australia, Sweden, the United Kingdom, hundreds of species specific protection plans ensued.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Notably the United Nations acted to conserve sites of outstanding cultural or natural importance to the common heritage of mankind.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The programme was adopted by the General Conference of UNESCO in 1972.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] As of 2006, a total of 830 sites are listed: 644 cultural, 162 natural.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Other conservation developments, however, have taken hold throughout the world.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] India, for example, passed the Wildlife Protection Act, 1972.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In 1980, a significant development was the emergence of the urban conservation movement.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] A local organization was established in Birmingham, UK, a development followed in rapid succession in cities across the UK, then overseas.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Although perceived as a grassroots movement, its early development was driven by academic research into urban wildlife.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Initially perceived as radical, the movement's view of conservation being inextricably linked with other human activity has now become mainstream in conservation thought.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Considerable research effort is now directed at urban conservation biology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The Society for Conservation Biology originated in 1985.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The late 1990s saw increasing professionalism in the sector, with the maturing of organisations such as the Institute of Ecology and Environmental Management and the Society for the Environment.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Since 2000, the concept of landscape scale conservation has risen to prominence, with less emphasis being given to single-species or even single-habitat focused actions.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Instead an ecosystem approach is advocated by most mainstream conservationists, although concerns have been expressed by those working to protect some high-profile species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Ecology has clarified the workings of the biosphere; i.e., the complex interrelationships among humans, other species, and the physical environment.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The burgeoning human population and associated agriculture, industry, and the ensuing pollution, have demonstrated how easily ecological relationships can be disrupted.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] becoming extinct during any given time interval.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] It does not represent all marine species, just those that are readily fossilized.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Extinction rates are measured in a variety of ways.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists measure and apply statistical measures of fossil records, rates of habitat loss, and a multitude of other variables such as loss of biodiversity as a function of the rate of habitat loss and site occupancy to obtain such estimates.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] *The Theory of Island Biogeography* is possibly the most significant contribution toward the scientific understanding of both the process and how to measure the rate of species extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The current background extinction rate is estimated to be one species every few years.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Actual extinction rates are estimated to be orders of magnitudes higher.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] While this is important, it's worth noting that there are no models in existence that account for the complexity of unpredictable factors like species movement, a non-analog climate, changing species interactions, evolutionary rates on finer time scales, and many other stochastic variables.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The measure of ongoing species loss is made more complex by the fact that most of the Earth's species have not been described or evaluated.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Estimates vary greatly on how many species actually exist (estimated range: 3,600,000–111,700,000) to how many have received a species binomial (estimated range: 1.5–8 million).
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Less than 1 percent of all species that have been described beyond simply noting its existence.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] From these figures, the IUCN reports that 23 percent of vertebrates, 5 percent of invertebrates and 70 percent of plants that have been evaluated are designated as endangered or threatened.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Better knowledge is being constructed by The Plant List for actual numbers of species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Systematic conservation planning is an effective way to seek and identify efficient and effective types of reserve design to capture or sustain the highest priority biodiversity values and to work with communities in support of local ecosystems.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists regularly prepare detailed conservation plans for grant proposals or to effectively coordinate their plan of action and to identify best management practices (e.g.).
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Systematic strategies generally employ the services of Geographic Information Systems to assist in the decision-making process.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The SLOSS debate is often considered in planning.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation physiology was defined by Steven J.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation physiology is particularly relevant to practitioners in that it has the potential to generate cause-and-effect relationships and reveal the factors that contribute to population declines.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The Society for Conservation Biology is a global community of conservation professionals dedicated to advancing the science and practice of conserving biodiversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biology as a discipline reaches beyond biology, into subjects such as philosophy, law, economics, humanities, arts, anthropology, and education.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Within biology, conservation genetics and evolution are immense fields unto themselves, but these disciplines are of prime importance to the practice and profession of conservation biology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservationists introduce bias when they support policies using qualitative description, such as habitat *degradation*, or *healthy* ecosystems.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists advocate for reasoned and sensible management of natural resources and do so with a disclosed combination of science, reason, logic, and values in their conservation management plans.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This sort of advocacy is similar to the medical profession advocating for healthy lifestyle options, both are beneficial to human well-being yet remain scientific in their approach.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There is a movement in conservation biology suggesting a new form of leadership is needed to mobilize conservation biology into a more effective discipline that is able to communicate the full scope of the problem to society at large.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The movement proposes an adaptive leadership approach that parallels an adaptive management approach.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The concept is based on a new philosophy or leadership theory steering away from historical notions of power, authority, and dominance.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Adaptive conservation leadership is reflective and more equitable as it applies to any member of society who can mobilize others toward meaningful change using communication techniques that are inspiring, purposeful, and collegial.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Adaptive conservation leadership and mentoring programs are being implemented by conservation biologists through organizations such as the Aldo Leopold Leadership Program.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation may be classified as either in-situ conservation, which is protecting an endangered species in its natural habitat, or ex-situ conservation, which occurs outside the natural habitat.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In-situ conservation involves protecting or restoring the habitat.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Ex-situ conservation, on the other hand, involves protection outside of an organism's natural habitat, such as on reservations or in gene banks, in circumstances where viable populations may not be present in the natural habitat.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The conservation of habitats like forest, water or soil in its natural state is crucial for any species depending in it to thrive.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Making a new environment which looks alike the original is less effective than preserving original habitats.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] An approach in Nepal named reforestation campaign has helped increase the density and area covered by the original forests which proved to be better than creating entirely new environment after original one is let to lost.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Old Forests Store More Carbon than Young Ones as proved by latest researches, so it is more crucial to protect the old ones.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The reforestation campaign launched by Himalayan Adventure Therapy in Nepal basically visits the old forests in periodic basis which are vulnerable to loss of density and the area covered due to unplanned urbanization activities.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Then they plant the new saplings of same tree families of that existing forest in the areas where the old forest has been lost and also plant those saplings to the barren areas connected to the forest.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This maintains the density and area covered by the forest.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Also, non-interference may be used, which is termed a preservationist method.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Preservationists advocate for giving areas of nature and species a protected existence that halts interference from the humans.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In this regard, conservationists differ from preservationists in the social dimension, as conservation biology engages society and seeks equitable solutions for both society and ecosystems.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Some preservationists emphasize the potential of biodiversity in a world without humans.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Ecological monitoring is the systematic collection of data relevant to the ecology of a species or habitat at repeating intervals with defined methods.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Long-term monitoring for environmental and ecological metrics is an important part of any successful conservation initiative.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Unfortunately, long-term data for many species and habitats is not available in many cases.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] A lack of historical data on species populations, habitats, and ecosystems means that any current or future conservation work will have to make assumptions to determine if the work is having any effect on the population or ecosystem health.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Ecological monitoring can provide early warning signals of deleterious effects (from human activities or natural changes in an environment) on an ecosystem and its species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] In order for signs of negative trends in ecosystem or species health to be detected, monitoring methods must be carried out at appropriate time intervals, and the metric must be able to capture the trend of the population or habitat as a whole.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Long-term monitoring can include the continued measuring of many biological, ecological, and environmental metrics including annual breeding success, population size estimates, water quality, biodiversity (which can be measured in many way, i.e.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] When determining which metrics to monitor for a conservation project, it is important to understand how an ecosystem functions and what role different species and abiotic factors have within the system.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Another benefit of ecological monitoring is the hard evidence it provides scientists to use for advising policy makers and funding bodies about conservation efforts.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Not only is ecological monitoring data important for convincing politicians, funders, and the public why a conservation program is important to implement, but also to keep them convinced that a program should be continued to be supported.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There is plenty of debate on how conservation resources can be used most efficiently; even within ecological monitoring, there is debate on which metrics that money, time and personnel should be dedicated to for the best chance of making a positive impact.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The concept of bioindicators / indicator species can be applied to ecological monitoring as a way to investigate how pollution is affecting an ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Species like amphibians and birds are highly susceptible to pollutants in their environment due to their behaviours and physiological features that cause them to absorb pollutants at a faster rate than other species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Amphibians spend parts of their time in the water and on land, making them susceptible to changes in both environments.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] They also have very permeable skin that allows them to breathe and intake water, which means they also take any air or water-soluble pollutants in as well.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Birds often cover a wide range in habitat types annually, and also generally revisit the same nesting site each year.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This makes it easier for researchers to track ecological effects at both an individual and a population level for the species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Many conservation researchers believe that having a long-term ecological monitoring program should be a priority for conservation projects, protected areas, and regions where environmental harm mitigation is used.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists are interdisciplinary researchers that practice ethics in the biological and social sciences.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Chan states that conservationists must advocate for biodiversity and can do so in a scientifically ethical manner by not promoting simultaneous advocacy against other competing values.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Aldo Leopold was a classical thinker and writer on such conservation ethics whose philosophy, ethics and writings are still valued and revisited by modern conservation biologists.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) has organized a global assortment of scientists and research stations across the planet to monitor the changing state of nature in an effort to tackle the extinction crisis.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The IUCN provides annual updates on the status of species conservation through its Red List.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The IUCN Red List serves as an international conservation tool to identify those species most in need of conservation attention and by providing a global index on the status of biodiversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] More than the dramatic rates of species loss, however, conservation scientists note that the sixth mass extinction is a biodiversity crisis requiring far more action than a priority focus on rare, endemic or endangered species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Concerns for biodiversity loss covers a broader conservation mandate that looks at ecological processes, such as migration, and a holistic examination of biodiversity at levels beyond the species, including genetic, population and ecosystem diversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Extensive, systematic, and rapid rates of biodiversity loss threatens the sustained well-being of humanity by limiting supply of ecosystem services that are otherwise regenerated by the complex and evolving holistic network of genetic and ecosystem diversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] While the conservation status of species is employed extensively in conservation management, some scientists highlight that it is the common species that are the primary source of exploitation and habitat alteration by humanity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Moreover, common species are often undervalued despite their role as the primary source of ecosystem services.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] While most in the community of conservation science "stress the importance" of sustaining biodiversity, there is debate on how to prioritize genes, species, or ecosystems, which are all components of biodiversity (e.g.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The costs of discovering, naming, and mapping out the distribution of every species, they argue, is an ill-advised conservation venture.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] They reason it is better to understand the significance of the ecological roles of species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Biodiversity hotspots and coldspots are a way of recognizing that the spatial concentration of genes, species, and ecosystems is not uniformly distributed on the Earth's surface.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Those arguing in favor of setting priorities for coldspots point out that there are other measures to consider beyond biodiversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] They point out that emphasizing hotspots downplays the importance of the social and ecological connections to vast areas of the Earth's ecosystems where biomass, not biodiversity, reigns supreme.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] It is estimated that 36 percent of the Earth's surface, encompassing 38.9 percent of the worlds vertebrates, lacks the endemic species to qualify as biodiversity hotspot.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Moreover, measures show that maximizing protections for biodiversity does not capture ecosystem services any better than targeting randomly chosen regions.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Population level biodiversity (mostly in coldspots) are disappearing at a rate that is ten times that at the species level.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The level of importance in addressing biomass versus endemism as a concern for conservation biology is highlighted in literature measuring the level of threat to global ecosystem carbon stocks that do not necessarily reside in areas of endemism.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] A hotspot priority approach would not invest so heavily in places such as steppes, the Serengeti, the Arctic, or taiga.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] These areas contribute a great abundance of population (not species) level biodiversity and ecosystem services, including cultural value and planetary nutrient cycling.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Those in favor of the hotspot approach point out that species are irreplaceable components of the global ecosystem, they are concentrated in places that are most threatened, and should therefore receive maximal strategic protections.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This is a hotspot approach because the priority is set to target species level concerns over population level or biomass.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Species richness and genetic biodiversity contributes to and engenders ecosystem stability, ecosystem processes, evolutionary adaptability, and biomass.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Both sides agree, however, that conserving biodiversity is necessary to reduce the extinction rate and identify an inherent value in nature; the debate hinges on how to prioritize limited conservation resources in the most cost-effective way.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Conservation biologists have started to collaborate with leading global economists to determine how to measure the wealth and services of nature and to make these values apparent in global market transactions.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This system of accounting is called *natural capital* and would, for example, register the value of an ecosystem before it is cleared to make way for development.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The WWF publishes its *Living Planet Report* and provides a global index of biodiversity by monitoring approximately 5,000 populations in 1,686 species of vertebrate (mammals, birds, fish, reptiles, and amphibians) and report on the trends in much the same way that the stock market is tracked.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This method of measuring the global economic benefit of nature has been endorsed by the G8+5 leaders and the European Commission.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Nature sustains many ecosystem services that benefit humanity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Many of the Earth's ecosystem services are public goods without a market and therefore no price or value.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] When the *stock market* registers a financial crisis, traders on Wall Street are not in the business of trading stocks for much of the planet's living natural capital stored in ecosystems.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There is no natural stock market with investment portfolios into sea horses, amphibians, insects, and other creatures that provide a sustainable supply of ecosystem services that are valuable to society.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The ecological footprint of society has exceeded the bio-regenerative capacity limits of the planet's ecosystems by about 30 percent, which is the same percentage of vertebrate populations that have registered decline from 1970 through 2005.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] There is a relationship, a correlation, between markets and natural capital, and social income inequity and biodiversity loss.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This means that there are greater rates of biodiversity loss in places where the inequity of wealth is greatest, an example of this would be the Perdido Key beach mouse.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This is an endangered species that its demis started because of continued development along beaches, these mice leave in sand dunes and play an important role within this ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] These mice help the grass grow inside the sandunes, they eat this grass and then this leads to then spreading seeds throughout the beach creating more grass.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Sand dunes may not seem that important but they do act as a barrier for any sort of storm coming from the ocean such as hurricanes.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Although a direct market comparison of natural capital is likely insufficient in terms of human value, one measure of ecosystem services suggests the contribution amounts to trillions of dollars yearly.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] For example, one segment of North American forests has been assigned an annual value of 250 billion dollars; as another example, honey bee pollination is estimated to provide between 10 and 18 billion dollars of value yearly.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The value of ecosystem services on one New Zealand island has been imputed to be as great as the GDP of that region.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] This planetary wealth is being lost at an incredible rate as the demands of human society is exceeding the bio-regenerative capacity of the Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] While biodiversity and ecosystems are resilient, the danger of losing them is that humans cannot recreate many ecosystem functions through technological innovation.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Some species, called a *keystone species* form a central supporting hub unique to their ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The loss of such a species results in a collapse in ecosystem function, as well as the loss of coexisting species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Keystone species are usually predators due to their ability to control the population of prey in their ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The importance of a keystone species was shown by the extinction of the Steller's sea cow (*Hydrodamalis gigas*) through its interaction with sea otters, sea urchins, and kelp.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Kelp beds grow and form nurseries in shallow waters to shelter creatures that support the food chain.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Sea urchins feed on kelp, while sea otters feed on sea urchins.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] With the rapid decline of sea otters due to overhunting, sea urchin populations grazed unrestricted on the kelp beds and the ecosystem collapsed.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Left unchecked, the urchins destroyed the shallow water kelp communities that supported the Steller's sea cow's diet and hastened their demise.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The sea otter was thought to be a keystone species because the coexistence of many ecological associates in the kelp beds relied upon otters for their survival.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] However this was later questioned by Turvey and Risley, who showed that hunting alone would have driven the Steller's sea cow extinct.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] An *indicator species* has a narrow set of ecological requirements, therefore they become useful targets for observing the health of an ecosystem.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Some animals, such as amphibians with their semi-permeable skin and linkages to wetlands, have an acute sensitivity to environmental harm and thus may serve as a *miner's canary*.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Indicator species are monitored in an effort to capture environmental degradation through pollution or some other link to proximate human activities.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Government regulators, consultants, or NGOs regularly monitor indicator species, however, there are limitations coupled with many practical considerations that must be followed for the approach to be effective.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] It is generally recommended that multiple indicators (genes, populations, species, communities, and landscape) be monitored for effective conservation measurement that prevents harm to the complex, and often unpredictable, response from ecosystem dynamics (Noss, 1997).
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] An example of an *umbrella species* is the monarch butterfly, because of its lengthy migrations and aesthetic value.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] The monarch migrates across North America, covering multiple ecosystems and so requires a large area to exist.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Any protections afforded to the monarch butterfly will at the same time umbrella many other species and habitats.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] An umbrella species is often used as *flagship species*, which are species, such as the giant panda, the blue whale, the tiger, the mountain gorilla and the monarch butterfly, that capture the public's attention and attract support for conservation measures.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p01] Paradoxically, however, conservation bias towards flagship species sometimes threatens other species of chief concern.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biologists study trends and process from the paleontological past to the ecological present as they gain an understanding of the context related to species extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] It is generally accepted that there have been five major global mass extinctions that register in Earth's history.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] These include: the Ordovician (440 mya), Devonian (370 mya), Permian–Triassic (252 mya), Triassic–Jurassic (201 mya), and Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event (66 mya) extinction spasms.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The latest *Living Planet Report* by the World Wide Fund for Nature estimates that we have exceeded the bio-regenerative capacity of the planet, requiring 1.6 Earths to support the demands placed on our natural resources.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biologists are dealing with and have published evidence from all corners of the planet indicating that humanity may be causing the sixth and fastest planetary extinction event.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] It has been suggested that an unprecedented number of species is becoming extinct in what is known as the Holocene extinction event.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The global extinction rate may be approximately 1,000 times higher than the natural background extinction rate.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] It is estimated that two-thirds of all mammal genera and one-half of all mammal species weighing at least 44 kilograms (97 lb) have gone extinct in the last 50,000 years.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The Global Amphibian Assessment reports that amphibians are declining on a global scale faster than any other vertebrate group, with over 32 percent of all surviving species being threatened with extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The surviving populations are in continual decline in 43 percent of those that are threatened.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Since the mid-1980s the actual rates of extinction have exceeded 211 times rates measured from the fossil record.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] However, "The current amphibian extinction rate may range from 25,039 to 45,474 times the background extinction rate for amphibians." The global extinction trend occurs in every major vertebrate group that is being monitored.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] For example, 23 percent of all mammals and 12 percent of all birds are Red Listed by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), meaning they too are threatened with extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Even though extinction is natural, the decline in species is happening at such an incredible rate that evolution can simply not match, therefore, leading to the greatest continual mass extinction on Earth.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Humans have dominated the planet and our high consumption of resources, along with the pollution generated is affecting the environments in which other species live.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] There are a wide variety of species that humans are working to protect such as the Hawaiian Crow and the Whooping Crane of Texas.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] People can also take action on preserving species by advocating and voting for global and national policies that improve climate, under the concepts of climate mitigation and climate restoration.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The Earth's oceans demand particular attention as climate change continues to alter pH levels, making it uninhabitable for organisms with shells which dissolve as a result.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Global assessments of coral reefs of the world continue to report drastic and rapid rates of decline.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] By 2000, 27 percent of the world's coral reef ecosystems had effectively collapsed.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The largest period of decline occurred in a dramatic "bleaching" event in 1998, where approximately 16 percent of all the coral reefs in the world disappeared in less than a year.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] *Coral bleaching* is caused by a mixture of environmental stresses, including increases in ocean temperatures and acidity, causing both the release of symbiotic algae and death of corals.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Decline and extinction risk in coral reef biodiversity has risen dramatically in the past ten years.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The loss of coral reefs, which are predicted to go extinct in the next century, threatens the balance of global biodiversity, will have huge economic impacts, and endangers food security for hundreds of millions of people.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation biology plays an important role in international agreements covering the world's oceans and other issues pertaining to biodiversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The oceans are threatened by acidification due to an increase in CO2 levels.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] This is a most serious threat to societies relying heavily upon oceanic natural resources.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] A concern is that the majority of all marine species will not be able to evolve or acclimate in response to the changes in the ocean chemistry.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The prospects of averting mass extinction seems unlikely when "90% of all of the large (average approximately ≥50 kg), open ocean tuna, billfishes, and sharks in the ocean" are reportedly gone.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Given the scientific review of current trends, the ocean is predicted to have few surviving multi-cellular organisms with only microbes left to dominate marine ecosystems.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Serious concerns also being raised about taxonomic groups that do not receive the same degree of social attention or attract funds as the vertebrates.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] These include fungal (including lichen-forming species), invertebrate (particularly insect) and plant communities where the vast majority of biodiversity is represented.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservation of fungi and conservation of insects, in particular, are both of pivotal importance for conservation biology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] As mycorrhizal symbionts, and as decomposers and recyclers, fungi are essential for sustainability of forests.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The value of insects in the biosphere is enormous because they outnumber all other living groups in measure of species richness.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The greatest bulk of biomass on land is found in plants, which is sustained by insect relations.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] This great ecological value of insects is countered by a society that often reacts negatively toward these aesthetically 'unpleasant' creatures.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] One area of concern in the insect world that has caught the public eye is the mysterious case of missing honey bees (*Apis mellifera*).
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Honey bees provide an indispensable ecological services through their acts of pollination supporting a huge variety of agriculture crops.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The use of honey and wax have become vastly used throughout the world.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The sudden disappearance of bees leaving empty hives or colony collapse disorder (CCD) is not uncommon.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] However, in 16-month period from 2006 through 2007, 29 percent of 577 beekeepers across the United States reported CCD losses in up to 76 percent of their colonies.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] This sudden demographic loss in bee numbers is placing a strain on the agricultural sector.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The cause behind the massive declines is puzzling scientists.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Pests, pesticides, and global warming are all being considered as possible causes.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Another highlight that links conservation biology to insects, forests, and climate change is the mountain pine beetle (*Dendroctonus ponderosae*) epidemic of British Columbia, Canada, which has infested 470,000 km2 (180,000 sq mi) of forested land since 1999.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] An action plan has been prepared by the Government of British Columbia to address this problem.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] A large proportion of parasite species are threatened by extinction.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] A few of them are being eradicated as pests of humans or domestic animals; however, most of them are harmless.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Parasites also make up a significant amount of global biodiversity, given that they make up a large proportion of all species on earth, making them of increasingly prevalent conservation interest.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Threats include the decline or fragmentation of host populations, or the extinction of host species.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Parasites are intricately woven into ecosystems and food webs, thereby occupying valuable roles in ecosystem structure and function.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Today, many threats to biodiversity exist.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] An acronym that can be used to express the top threats of present-day H.I.P.P.O stands for Habitat Loss, Invasive Species, Pollution, Human Population, and Overharvesting.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The primary threats to biodiversity are habitat destruction (such as deforestation, agricultural expansion, urban development), and overexploitation (such as wildlife trade).
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Habitat fragmentation also poses challenges, because the global network of protected areas only covers 11.5 percent of the Earth's surface.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] A significant consequence of fragmentation and lack of linked protected areas is the reduction of animal migration on a global scale.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Considering that billions of tonnes of biomass are responsible for nutrient cycling across the Earth, the reduction of migration is a serious matter for conservation biology.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] However, human activities need not necessarily cause irreparable harm to the biosphere.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] With conservation management and planning for biodiversity at all levels, from genes to ecosystems, there are examples where humans mutually coexist in a sustainable way with nature.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Even with the current threats to biodiversity there are ways we can improve the current condition and start anew.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Many of the threats to biodiversity, including disease and climate change, are reaching inside borders of protected areas, leaving them 'not-so protected' (e.g.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Climate change, for example, is often cited as a serious threat in this regard, because there is a feedback loop between species extinction and the release of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Ecosystems store and cycle large amounts of carbon which regulates global conditions.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] In present day, there have been major climate shifts with temperature changes making survival of some species difficult.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The effects of global warming add a catastrophic threat toward a mass extinction of global biological diversity.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Numerous more species are predicted to face unprecedented levels of extinction risk due to population increase, climate change and economic development in the future.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] Conservationists have claimed that not all the species can be saved, and they have to decide which their efforts should be used to protect.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] This concept is known as the Conservation Triage.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The extinction threat is estimated to range from 15 to 37 percent of all species by 2050, or 50 percent of all species over the next 50 years.
[src:conservation-biology/conservation-biology-p02] The current extinction rate is 100–100,000 times more rapid today than the last several billion years.
